  "prompt": "How do you determine the pH of hydrofluoric acid?",
  "response": "To determine the pH of hydrofluoric acid (HF), you can follow these steps:\n\n1. **Understand the Acid Strength**: Hydrofluoric acid is a weak acid, meaning it does not fully dissociate in solution. The dissociation can be represented by the equation:\n   \\[\n   \\text{HF} \\rightleftharpoons \\text{H}^+ + \\text{F}^-\n   \\]\n\n2. **Use the Acid Dissociation Constant (Ka)**: The dissociation of HF can be described by the acid dissociation constant \\( K_a \\). For HF, \\( K_a \\) is typically around \\( 6.6 \\times 10^{-4} \\) at 25 \u00b0C.\n\n3. **Set Up the Equilibrium Expression**: The equilibrium expression for the dissociation of HF is:\n   \\[\n   K_a = \\frac{[\\text{H}^+][\\text{F}^-]}{[\\text{HF}]}\n   \\]\n\n4. **Initial Concentration**: If you know the initial concentration of HF (let's denote it as \\( C \\)), you can set up an ICE (Initial, Change, Equilibrium) table:\n   - Initial: \\[ [\\text{HF}] = C, \\quad [\\text{H}^+] = 0, \\quad [\\text{F}^-] = 0 \\]\n   - Change: \\[ [\\text{HF}] = C - x, \\quad [\\text{H}^+] = x, \\quad [\\text{F}^-] = x \\]\n   - Equilibrium: \\[ [\\text{HF}] = C - x, \\quad [\\text{H}^+] = x, \\quad [\\text{F}^-] = x \\]\n\n5. **Substitute into the \\( K_a \\) Expression**:\n   \\[\n   K_a = \\frac{x^2}{C - x}\n   \\]\n   Assuming \\( x \\) is small compared to \\( C \\) (which is usually valid), you can simplify this to:\n   \\[\n   K_a \\approx \\frac{x^2}{C}\n   \\]\n\n6. **Solve for \\( x \\)** (which is \\( [\\text{H}^+] \\)):\n   \\[\n   x^2 = K_a \\cdot C\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   x = \\sqrt{K_a \\cdot C}\n   \\]\n\n7. **Calculate the pH**: The pH is then calculated using:\n   \\[\n   \\text{pH} = -\\log[\\text{H}^+]\n   \\]\n   Substituting \\( x \\) into the equation gives:\n   \\[\n   \\text{pH} = -\\log\\left(\\sqrt{K_a \\cdot C}\\right) = -\\frac{1}{2}\\log(K_a) - \\frac{1}{2}\\log(C)\n   \\]\n\n8. **Example Calculation**: If you have a 0.1 M solution of HF:\n   \\[\n   K_a = 6.6 \\times 10^{-4}, \\quad C = 0.1\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   [\\text{H}^+] = \\sqrt{6.6 \\times 10^{-4} \\cdot 0.1} = \\sqrt{6.6 \\times 10^{-5}} \\approx 8.12 \\times 10^{-3} \\, \\text{M}\n   \\]\n   \\[\n   \\text{pH} = -\\log(8.12 \\times 10^{-3}) \\approx 2.09\n   \\]\n\nBy following these steps, you can determine the pH of hydrofluoric acid in solution based on its concentration.",
